pullRequest.body:
`Int.strongRec`: if a proposition holds for integers less than a threshold, and it holds  for an integer above the threshold if it holds for all smaller integers, then it holds for all integers.

`negOnePow_abs` says (-1)^|n|=(-1)^n

`pos_iff_two_le_of_even` and `lt_iff_add_two_le_of_even_sub` are two lemmas about the interaction of parity and the order on the integers.

`Equiv.Perm.closure_isSwap` is strengthened to say the sub**monoid** generated by transpositions is the whole group, and moreover show transpositions of adjacent elements are enough.

Is there a reason to reorder this proof? I'm not convinced the new code is necessarily better.
I think I originally wanted to golf it but didn't end up finding any golf ... let me change it back.
I don't see `IsSwap` in the statement, so I don't think the name should have `isSwap` either
hanks! forgot to change the name, should say `swap` instead.

To be consistent with the naming of the other recursors in this file, and minor golf:
```suggestion
@[elab_as_elim] protected def strongInduction {P : â„¤ â†’ Sort*} (m : â„¤) (lt : âˆ€ n < m, P n)
    (ge : âˆ€ n â‰¥ m, (âˆ€ k : â„¤, k < n â†’ P k) â†’ P n) (n : â„¤) : P n :=
  (em <| n < m).by_cases (lt n) fun h â†¦ ge n (not_lt.mp h) <| n.inductionOn' m lt
    (fun _ _ hn l lt1 â†¦ (em <| l < m).by_cases (lt l) fun nlt â†¦ ge l (not_lt.mp nlt)
      fun n lt2 â†¦ hn n <| lt_of_lt_of_le lt2 <| lt_add_one_iff.mp lt1)
    fun n _ hn l lt1 â†¦ hn l <| lt1.trans n.pred_self_lt
```
Note that I am very much against this naming, but we should change them in a future PR.

Personally I think this is too terse - maybe pattern-matching using `induction` would be easier to read.

Just to be clear, you also think that recursors that eliminate into Sort* should be called `Rec` rather than `Induction`, right? And you want to change them all in a future PR? I think it's okay to give this new recursor the correct name, even if it's inconsistent with everything else in this file; it's at least consistent with [Nat.strongRec](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Batteries/Data/Nat/Basic.html#Nat.strongRec). Or do you have issues with the name `strongRec`?

> Personally I think this is too terse - maybe pattern-matching using `induction` would be easier to read.

Does `induction` work with Sort* valued stuff? I think term mode is usually preferred for definitions (not lemmas).
Note that Lean doesn't know â„¤ is a linear order in this file, so we cannot use `not_lt`, `lt_of_lt_of_le` and `lt_trans` and have to resort to the corresponding `Int.` lemmas, which are protected.

Seems to work:
```suggestion
  add_one_le_iff.symm.trans <| Ne.le_iff_lt <| by rintro rfl; exact not_even_one even
```
Yeah, exploiting some nice defeq :)

Unless a proof is very short, it's in general more readable to have a full tactic mode proof. So
```suggestion
    Submonoid.closure (Set.range fun i : Fin n â†¦ swap i.castSucc i.succ) = âŠ¤ := by
  apply top_unique
```
and then unindent the rest.
done
That's really hard to read (although extremely efficient!). Can you come up with something more explicit?

The whole type is simply too long and doesn't even fit in one line, so I added a comment
`-- swap i j.succ âˆˆ Submonoid.closure ... (the LHS)`

I still think this is not good style, because when you read the proof `mem` is not assigned (even its type), so there is no way the reader can understand what is going on even using the goal view. Even if the type takes two or three lines, you should just write it down to help your reader.

For instance,
```lean
  have mem : swap j.castSucc j.succ âˆˆ Submonoid.closure 
      (Set.range fun (i : Fin n) â†¦ swap i.castSucc i.succ) := Submonoid.subset_closure âŸ¨_, rflâŸ©
  obtain rfl | lts := (Fin.le_castSucc_iff.mpr lt).eq_or_lt
  Â· exact mem
  rw [swap_comm, â† swap_mul_swap_mul_swap (y := Fin.castSucc j) lts.ne lt.ne]
  exact mul_mem (mul_mem mem <| ih lts.ne lts) mem
```
is not longer than what you have written, but the reader can see what is going on (and there is one indentation level less).

An indication that the proof was not so easy to follow is that the type you indicated in your previous comment is not the right one :-)
Okay thanks. I think I copied the goal rather than the type of `mem` ðŸ¤¦

To me this looks like golfing at its worst, i.e., making sure that if the proof breaks then it is extremely hard to fix :-)
Would it make sense to have a more readable tactic proof? (I'm not sure because this could also be constructing data, and in this case having a term like you do is probably a good idea). An intermediate stance would be to add comments explaining what the different steps are doing.

I think term-mode proofs like this is quite hard to break; it only breaks if you remove the lemmas used or change explicitness of arguments, and it's clear how to fix after those changes.

If I had done it in tactic mode I probably would keep it Prop valued rather than Sort*.
Â 
And I think this falls into the "mathematically trivial" sort of lemma/def that ought to be made as short as possible, and there isn't much point explaining the steps. Part of the reason this is long is that it's in a basic file that doesn't know Int is a LinearOrder, so some order lemmas with names suitable for dot notation can't be used. I have now changed the term-mode proofs to `by omega`.

I just supplied a [proof](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/13153/commits/dc5b524898df864d943cc84b90cd36033901728e#diff-88019217cf2ac044faaf33356a0730a7360bc165882bd624b8ccde2e8f93ef1fR366-R377) that `strongRec` satisfies the expected recurrence relation which uniquely specifies it; for this I first need to prove the recurrence relations for `Int.inductionOn'`, which is somewhat painful, and suggestion of better proofs (or even modification of the definition) would be welcome.

```suggestion
    clear ne
    induction' j using Fin.induction with j ih
```
Normally one tactic per line, unless it's a one-liner. (You can also safely just remove the `clear ne`, and fix the proof below).
removed and fixed the proof
I am adding a very very similar result in #13683. Actually it's more general, so I think you will be able to drop your lemma entirely
